# The upstream serves correct replies and does nothing exotic: this scenario's
# subject is the NGINX side of a USR2 binary upgrade, not a backend fault. The
# oracle is purely the accept count in the journal -- a request answered by a
# freshly-execed worker must OPEN a new upstream connection, because the new
# worker inherited none of the old worker's keepalive pool. The backend only has
# to serve correctly and let the journal count accepts.
#
# Gated by backend-smoke: this fake is proven to serve correctly when told to
# behave normally, so a missing accept here is a module fact, not a fake defect.
proto   memcached
seed    k       usr2-keepalive-value
